description.text: Print your own token for communing with Great Old Ones! I designed these as tokens for a 2011 Halloween party. Edge is higher than the symbol to reduce wear and tear. Now available on Github: https://github.com/bld/Necronomicoin

I printed this on a Makergear Mosaic with:
  • 0.25 mm layer thickness
  • 0.4 mm line thickness
  • 1.0 infill
  • 0 extra shells
    I used Multiply to print 9 at once.
    Firmware without lookahead acceleration (Sprinter vs. Marlin) produced an interesting effect: pronounced edges at each corner of the outer cylinder. This gave them and old school character.
    Text object created with text2surface, and polygons reduced with Meshlab. Necronomicon symbol created in QCAD.

This is my design for a kazoo (spanish 'turuta'). It is a very simple musical instrument and a really simple to use one. Very clever and funny to use, and very popular here in Spain in almost any party. So easy to use that even a kid could make wonders with it. It just require a piece of waxpaper, cooking film, or even a piece of a plastic bag. Put it inside the cap (just press the cap into the hole). Then you can use your vocal strings (hum) to make the membrane vibrate and output your voice with a caracteristic and impressive tone added. See the wiki for 'kazoo' for more info. If you want to be the king of the kazoo players just use the trumpet style cap!! I have made this for my nephew, and he has spent lots of funny moments with me playing tunes together. Recommended, One of the funniest thing I have ever made... PLA recommended printing as of the height, Body requires support from platform only, common and easy for all slicers nowadays.

Enjoy it as my nephew and I do!!!

HINT: DON'T TENSE THE MEMBRANE!!! It would work better as free as the membrane is. So you have only to keep tight on the borders, Assure the inner face is NOT tight.

UPDATE (17-JUN-2016): Added a plain cap and a trumpet style cap, just in case. Don't use this if you have a big nose!! You want more? Ok, Let it be royal, let's make the king of the kazoos, Let's make a cap with a crown!! Let's make the Kingzoo!!! I'm going crazy... hahahah. Let's the party start...

UPDATE (16-JUN-2016): Enhanced acoustics. Cap diameter increased to allow better bass. Extra air exit decreased to increase resonance/armonics. Mouthpiece size decreased to allow a better fit on kid's mouths ;-). Changed cap design to interactuate more with the membrane, now protection touches the membrane. No updates expected for the kazoo body. Maybe some extras for the cap... stay tuned!!

comments.text: Nice work, this thing prints and works well. I used the trumpet cap and tin foil for the membrane. I also added set screws to secure the cap. As the maker states, proper tension, or lack of, is key to getting a good sound. And by good I mean super loud and crazy raspy. Prints great, nice design. Thanks for sharing!

description.text:
To demonstrate how simple lever tool can be used and the Law of the lever.
A box or cylinder can be used filled with weight like a penny or other items. It can demonstrate the three different classes of levers. During the design and contraction process, the use of basic 3D geometry has been used.

Printer:

Malan M180

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

How I Designed This

To create the lever, which consists of three parts, the addition and subtraction of the basic geometric shapes has been used. The lever is formed by a box. The weight are design by a box and cylinder and formed by a cutaway cylinder and box to hollow out the weight to let the student fill with different weighted items like penny, water, ect,.. The student can design different sizes of the weights and shorten or lengthen the lever. All parts are designed for 3D printing

Project: Lever System

Object
Students will be able to test and use in practice how lever work with fulcrum, motion, resistance and effort. Students will find out how to change the fulcrum and how much effort to lift the load or balance out the load.

Wikipedia - Lever

Weight of Coins

The may also work with inventing their own design of the lever, in order to meet the principle, while being as simple and compact as possible.

Audience

The function of the lever tool is usually part of the curriculum of the secondary school or students learning about engineering and math.

Preparation

The preparation for this project is the study of the fundamental mathematical principles.
Material: You also need items like penny’s, or other things that has weight. May require a scale to measure the weight of the items to put in the box or cylinder. The penny weight for a copper penny is 2.500 grams. You will need a 3D printer. No tools required.

Steps

Students first create the M1 & M2 box or cylinder, fulcrum & plank.
Adding penny to M1 & M2 and adjusting the 3D object along the plank “lever” and calculate the force and levers. A lever is a beam connected to ground by a hinge, or pivot, called a fulcrum. The ideal lever does not dissipate or store energy, which means there is no friction in the hinge or bending in the beam. In this case, the power into the lever equals the power out, and the ratio of output to input force is given by the ratio of the distances from the fulcrum to the points of application of these forces. This is known as the law of the lever.

T1 = F1a, T2 = F2b

where F1 is the input force to the lever and F2 is the output force. The distances a and b are the perpendicular distances between the forces and the fulcrum.
Since the moments of torque must be balanced,

T1 = T2. So, F1a = F2b

The mechanical advantage of the lever is the ratio of output force to input force,

MA = F2/F1 = a/b

This relationship shows that the mechanical advantage can be computed from ratio of the distances from the fulcrum to where the input and output forces are applied to the lever, assuming no losses due to friction, flexibility or wear.

Fulcrum in the middle: the effort is applied on one side of the fulcrum and the resistance (or load) on the other side, for example, a seesaw, a crowbar or a pair of scissors. Mechanical advantage may be greater or less than 1. Resistance (or load) in the middle: the effort is applied on one side of the resistance and the fulcrum is located on the other side, for example, a wheelbarrow, a nutcracker, a bottle opener or the brake pedal of a car. Mechanical advantage is always greater than 1. Effort in the middle: the resistance (or load) is on one side of the effort and the fulcrum is located on the other side, for example, a pair of tweezers or the human mandible. Mechanical advantage is always less than 1. Results

The students of lower grades can construct various weights, blocks and cylinders layout for this project. Students of higher grades can design their own lever and 3D objects to measure the different classes of levers. Learn about the classes of levers.

title: LED Work Light bracket for Geeetech  Prusa I3

description.text:
The bracket allows you to mount two LED strips on the X carriage, so they shine on the item being printed.
The LED strips I am using (because I have them) are by Diatone, but others speced for operation at 12 volts should work OK. http://www.banggood.com/Diatone-3-4S-LED-Decoration-Board-Strip-Set-For-250-Class-Frame-p-961260.html
There are 4 LED strips in the item: white, red, green, and blue. I'll only be using the white ones. They current cost from one supplier is about $1.50 per item (4 led strips). They are wired into the 12V fan power which is always on. I' probably add a small switch so they can be turned off; they are really bright!

Each white LED strips draws 10 milliamps with 12 volts across it, so the additional current load is minimal.

There are three items to print: the splint for stabilizing the two brackets, the left bracket found here, and the right bracket which is a mirror image of the left bracket created at print time.

The dark photo of the LED illumination may look like the illumination isn't very bright, but the exposure was reduced to make the light distribution more visible. It appears there will be more than enough light to observe the surface as it prints.

EDIT 12/9/16
It took me a while to realize that the LEDs should be moved closer to the extruder so the work is lighted better. I added some washers that you can use with a longer screw to move the lights forward. Scale the Z axis to get the length you need. I also scaled X&Y by 1.1 to make sure they fit without having to file the hole.

Notes:

Nothing beyond ordinary cleanup is required. The hole will probably need some cleanup since the top is bridged during printing.
The small rectangular splint can be attached to one side only. It's purpose is to prevent one or both of the LED panels from dropping down into the work space if a screw should come loose. It can be attached after the panels are attached to the carriage, or before mounting providing only one side is glued. There should be a small space between the arms if the hole spacing is 30 mm.

description.text:
Regalhalter für ein DVD / Blu-ray Disc Regal. Es wird noch ein passender Regalboden aus Glas oder Plexiglas mit 10mm Stärke und 14,5cm Breite benötigt. Der Regalboden kann dann von hinten mit einem LED-Streifen beleuchtet werden. In den seitlichen Haltern ist dafür Platz vorgesehen.
Die Halter sind in Unterteil und Seitenteil aufgeteilt. Das Seitenteil wird mit Klebstoff und 2-3 Schrauben an das Unterteil montiert.
Das Unterteil kann entweder am Stück mit Support oder in getrennten Drucken gedruckt werden. Dann müssen die Teile zusammengeklebt werden.
Die Seitenteile ...film-li-led / film-re-led haben Aussparungen für die Kabelzuführungen der LED-Streifen.
Das Seitenteil ...Seite_voll kann, z.B. über Tinkercad mit einem passenden Logo ausgestanzt werden. Ich habe dies so mit dem DVD und Blu-ray Logo so gemacht.
Für längere Regale kann der Mittelhalter als Unterstützung montiert werden.

Shelf support for a DVD or Blu-ray disc shelf. You have to buy the shelf floor in glass or Plexiglas (10mm strong, 14,5 cm wide). You can iluminate the shelf floor with a led Strip mounted in the back of the floor. In the shelf supports there is left space for the led stripes.
The support-part can be printed out as one part (Supports are needed) or in three parts w/0 Supports. Then you have to glue the parts together.
The sideparts are glued to the supportpart and secured with 2 - 3 screws.
The sideparts ...film-li-led and film-re-led have cutouts for the powersupply to led-stripes.
The sidepart ...Seite_voll can used in Tinerkad to cut out a logo of your choice. I have done so with a DVD and a Blu-ray Logo.
For longer shelfs, there is an extrasupport (Mittelhalter).

title: 2000 Flushes holder for Gerber pressure-assist toilet

description.text:
Okay, so who else might need this?  Probably no one.  But... here ya go.  Possible grossness ahead.  
There's a lot of great things about pressure-assist toilets, but there's one odd disadvantage: those little blue bricks that you can throw into the tank of the toilet, you can't throw those in because there's no open water in the tank.  
So this clips onto the side of the bowl and holds a "2000 Flushes" brick in the water.  That's it.  
The full design is too big to print on an 8"x8" print bed like my Solidoodle 3, and may even be too big for a 9"x6" unit like the FlashForge Creator.  So there's also a two-piece version that can be held together with a simple bolt.  
Now that I've finally printed one, I don't know how likely it is I could use it.  There's just not enough room in the toilet.  It's fine for number one, but number two would be a problem.

description.text:
Do you have the need to accurately measure out small amounts of baby shampoo?
Do you hate the mess and cleanup when using a measuring spoon for this task?

If you answered yes to these questions then this is your lucky day.

With the Baby Shampoo Syringe Adapter, you can now use a syringe to remove your preferred volume of shampoo directly from the bottle. From there you can inject the shampoo directly where you need it without any mess or waste!

Just pop the top of your J&J Baby Shampoo Bottle, jam this adapter in the hole, add a syringe and you are all ready to measure shampoo like the cool kids. For less than 5 cents worth of plastic, this miracle adapter can be yours today!

The syringe had a luer-lok tip, just some screw threads. These were carefully cut off to reveal the bare syringe tip. A few seconds with a hobby knife was all it took. Just be careful not to cut the tip clear off like I did the first time.

The FreeCAD file is provided in case you wanted to adapt this for a different syringe tip.

Update: 6/16/16 I've gone ahead and made a change to allow this to use syringes that we can find at the drug store. I'll print and test, but in the time being, version 2 should be more universally used.

Update:6/17/16 OK, version 2 didn't do the trick since now the original syringe was too loose. I'll crack this nut yet. Version 2 removed.

Update: 2/21/16 Finally got a decent model going that will handle both of the syringes that I have on hand. This will take over the existing files and is labeled as 'universal'. Share and enjoy.

description.text:
NORTHERN ONLY

This is a segmented version Digital Sundial Cleansed by Margu, which was a cleaned-up remix of the original Digital Sundial by Mojoptix.

This version is simply a broken-up version of the Cleansed Sundial. It's segmented into four parts which allows for failure of one or more segments without the loss of the entire print. The first and forth segments are the most likely to be successful with the middle two prone to failure due to their many light blocking bridges. I've marked each piece to indicate the piece that it mates to with dimples. Match one dimple to one dimple, two dimples to two dimples, and so-forth. I've also added pegs and holes to assist in aligning the segments when you glue them together.

The first and last segments can be printed with .2 resolution whereas the middle two segments need .1 or .15.

My apologies as I only created the Northern Hemisphere.

Please also see my Sundial test for testing your printer's bridging ability as it pertains to the sundial before committing to a print: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1568322

Please see Sundial Cleansed for a description of why and how Margu made this version of the digital sundial: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1149469

And of course the original digital sundial by Mojoptix for a description of the original project and to get the other sundial parts like the stand/mount for it: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1068443

I imported Margu's cleansed sundial into MS 3D Builder and sliced it between the various digits and then used object cylinder creation for the pegs and the holes and used emboss for the identification dimples. I then saved each segment to a unique .STL file.

description.text:
The Story
I needed some 7mm cableclamps, but i'm too lazy to bend my work-home route to a hardware store to buy them. I didn't like the more simple designs here on Thingiverse, so I copied the typical Dutch cableclamp design more or less.

Nail size
The nail has to be around 2mm thickness. If the nail goes in very tight, it might be an idea to heat the nail (hold it with some pliers), and melt it through the hole. If you smash a too big nail through the hole, the plastic might and probably will break.

If you don't own any spare nails, you can print the one that's available in this project :-) j/k

Other cable sizes
If you need any other size, just change the scale. Scale 1 = 7mm. so if you need 12mm, do 1 / 7 * 12 and type that number into the scale parameter in your slicer.

Here is a table for MM Diameter to scale conversion:

description.text:
This handlebar extender was made for my RadRover from Rad Power Bikes so I could center mount a flashlight. I made it extra wide in case I decide to mount anything else in the future. The handlerbar my bike came with was about 31.8 mm at the section where I wanted to install this.

I printed two of the rings separately. Then, I printed the extender bar.

Last, I printed the flashlight holder. This is meant to be coupled with a clamp I already have. You can skip this or find a better one. The extender bar is 25mm round for reference.

This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/jZ5LD9XoIX1

UPDATE:
Version 1 was a fail. The UltraFire flashlight I mounted to it was too heavy and the whole handlebar extender system broke when I went over a big bump.

Version 2
I've made a new version that has a lot more plastic around version 1's failure point. Crossing fingers that this design works better.

Version 3
Finally, a working model that I've tested to sufficiently carry a heavy flashlight without breaking.
https://tinkercad.com/things/3D1g9xVLxtC

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

Yes

.4

15%

Notes:

On my Robo 3D R1+ Plus, I used a raft and supports to print the extender bar. I chose to use a raft after my first 2 printing attempts resulted in the bar lifting off the bed. Simplify3D makes an easy to remove raft and pretty much guaranteed a successful print. I also printed this with the arms laid horizontal for strength so that the print lines ran up and down the arms. I was worried that if the arms were printed vertically, then they could easily snap off between layers.

For the rings, I printed them with no raft and no supports.

All pieces are meant to printed in place without rotation for optimal strength in the final print.

Assembly

To connect the rings to the extender, I used some 1 1/2 inch wood screws.

To connect the rings to the handlebar, you'll need to drill holes, then use some nuts and bolts. I used 12mm M3 bolts and M3 nuts myself.

I suggest using a shim or flatten a rubber band for the inside of the rings. This way you'll get better grip once it is installed.

title: Customizable Circle Cutting Jig for Harbor Freight Trim Router

description.text:
This is a customizable circle cutting jig for the $30 Harbor Freight trim router Item#61626.

Rather than be a tool that can be used for any project, I just wanted to make something quick for the particular project I was working on, namely XL-S Encore speaker set. So the OpenSCAD file has these 6 circle diameter values in it.

So I provide you the customizable scad file for you to modify to add the set of values you need for your project.

If someone has the urge to modify this circle jig to make it a tool that can be used on any project, without having to print out a new one each time, that would be awesome and please let me know if you do so, so I can download and print.

But as it is now, it only costs me 75 cents to print for the current job I'm working on. (I use the cheap $11.99 a roll filament from ebay.. excelevan.. cheapest color I can find lol).

Works great as you can see in the photo. I spent 75 cents to print this (actually $1.50 because I had to modify a value by 1.01mm in the scad file to make it perfect, and print a second time). And it saved me like $40. Actually more than that because the Jasper 200 jig is $40 but only fits certain routers that cost like $100 and I only had this cheap $30 Harbor Frieght router. I think I saved something like $140 or so. So I don't care that this is a single use jig hah. Can print another for 75 cents for a different job.

Any questions, please ask me in comments -- I'll answer.

Note: since the router isn't that powerful, i.e. trim router, don't try and take off too much in one pass.. might take a few passes. Also, I got the 1/8" stainless steel guide pin 3/4" long from Ace Hardware for 67 cents.

I printed at 100% infill. I don't know how 50% infill would hold up in comparison since there is a pin that needs to be tapped in with a hammer -- friction fit.

EDIT: The manufacturer uses some sort of soft glue on the threads of the 4 screws that hold this plate on. Be gentle re-tightening them, just using pretty much finger muscles on the screwdriver so they don't slip on the threads. Also when removing guide pin (usually with pliers) make sure to hold the plate down so you don't cause the screws to pop out of the loose threads. I am thinking about just drilling out the holes on the top plate permanently attached to the trim router and securing the base plate (or this jig) to it by running small bolts through it and securing on the top with a nut and washer. I don't think it'd interfere with any jobs right? Need to think on this one.

The 6 Packer is constructed of 3/16" thick laser cut ply wood and assembled with 4-40 1/2" screws and nuts. The bottle holes will accept anything from the run of the mill long neck bottles to IBCs to short chubby craft beer bottles.
The 6 Packer was designed with openscad and is completely parametric. You can change material thickness, bottle diameter, fastener size, hand grip size re-render and cut out using your favorite laser cutter!

• Tweak the OpenSCAD file to your exact specifications
  • Export from OpenSCAD as a DXF.

  • Import DXF into Inkscape

  • Prep & send to your laser cutter
  • Put all the pieces together
  • Smile with delight at your creation.

first extreme caution is needed as vapor of acetone is both highly flamible

I use a asparagus cooking pot and the cage

put a tablespoon of acetone in the pot
put the disc on the bottom of the cage and the model on top of the disc.
put cage in the pot
lid on pot tightly
put on a electric hotplate (preheated)
for 20 seconds
take pot off hotplate and let sit another 10 seconds
remove cage from pot and let air cool for a few minutes

author: chris420_

title: Turnigy Talon Quad Copter Motor Mounts

description.text:
These are super simple replacement motor mounts for my Turnigy Talon v2 quad copter but should fit any 14mm carbon tube.  
Standard mounting holes, should fit most small motors.  
*Update:  I have reinforced the top clamping section to make it significantly sturdier.

These are designed to use two M3x10mm or longer bolts and small hex nuts to fit.  
I used 35% infill on the motor mounts themselves and they are incredibly strong yet light weight (right at 13g).  
For the top clamping portion of the mount I suggest printing at 100% infill for maximum strength.  
Additionally, if you're using this to replace bent or broken motor mounts from your Turnigy Talon v2 you can use the aluminum clamps in place of the printed ones.  
The overall weight of the printed mount with screws is 18g, lighter than the original Talon mount at 26g, and much easier to replace.

Back panel for Wanhao Di3 v2 supports a 60mm fan with a small honeycomb grill.

The holes for the fan screws have been increased to accommodate 5mm case fan screws, slight countersink so they don't stick out too much

With that noise in mind I created an alternate model with a much larger honeycomb grill @ http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1629075 in case you have a fan which pushes more air and want to avoid noise
